Population-level impact of adverse early life conditions on adult healthy life 
expectancy in low- and middle-income countries.

Beltrán-Sánchez H(1), Palloni A(2)(3), Huangfu Y(2), McEniry M(2).

Author information:
(1)University of California, Los Angeles.
(2)University of Wisconsin-Madison.
(3)Consejo Superior de Investigaciones.

Evidence from theories of Developmental Origins of Health and Disease (DOHaD) 
suggests that experiencing adverse early life conditions subsequently leads to 
detrimental adult health outcomes. The bulk of empirical DOHaD literature does 
not consider the nature and magnitude of the impact of adverse early life 
conditions at the population level. In particular, it ignores the distortion of 
age and cohort patterns of adult health and mortality and the increased load of 
chronic illness and disability that ensues. In this paper, we use a 
microsimulation model combined with empirical estimates of incidence and 
prevalence of obesity, type 2 diabetes, and associated disability in low- and 
middle-income countries to assess the magnitude of delayed effects on adult 
healthy life expectancy and on compression (or expansion) of morbidity at older 
ages. The main goal is to determine if, in what ways, and to what extent delayed 
effects due to early conditions can influence cohorts' chronic illness and 
disability profiles.

