Why we should not extend the 14-day rule.

Blackshaw BP(1), Rodger D(2).

Author information:
(1)Department of Philosophy, University of Birmingham, Birmingham B15 2TT, UK 
bblackshaw@gmail.com.
(2)Allied Health Sciences, London South Bank University School of Health and 
Social Care, London, UK.

The 14-day rule restricts the culturing of human embryos in vitro for the 
purposes of scientific research for no longer than 14 days. Since researchers 
recently developed the capability to exceed the 14-day limit, pressure to modify 
the rule has started to build. Sophia McCully argues that the limit should be 
extended to 28 days, listing numerous potential benefits of doing so. We contend 
that McCully has not engaged with the main reasons why the Warnock Committee set 
such a limit, and these still remain valid. As a result, her case for an 
extension of the 14-day rule is not persuasive.

